Feature scaling¶

We standardize each feature to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1, separately on the train and test datasets.

In [18]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
In [19]:
# Fit the scaler on the training data
scaler = StandardScaler().fit(X_train)

# Transform the training data
X_train = pd.DataFrame(scaler.transform(X_train), columns=X_train.columns)

# Transform the test data using the same scaler
X_test = pd.DataFrame(scaler.transform(X_test), columns=X_test.columns)

Fitting the StandardScaler on the training data and then using the same scaler to transform both the training and test data is generally recommended, since it ensures that the scaling is consistent and prevents data leakage from the test set.

Correlation¶

Intuitively, highly correlated features carry redundant information. Since PCA identifies combinations of the original features that capture the most variance in the data and aims to reduce its dimensionality by combining correlated features into the so-called principal components, it is useful to understand the correlation structure of the data.

We can continue working on scaled data since the standardization does not affect correlation between variables, indeed it is defined as: $$\rho_{ij}:=\frac{\text{Cov}(X_i, X_j)}{\sigma_i\sigma_j}$$ and does not depend on the overall mean and standard deviation of the full train set.

In [22]:
correlation = X_train.corr()

We can simultaneously analyze the correlation among all features by means of a heatmap.

In [23]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 15))
sns.heatmap(X_train.corr(), cmap="YlGnBu", annot=True)
Out[23]:
<Axes: >

Most features are mildly correlated, thus applying PCA may be effective in reducing dimensionality, because there is "(at least) some redundancy" to eliminate.

We can also more evidently visualize this by only considering features with a significant correlation (e.g. more than 1/4 as correlation coefficient in absolute value).

We would like to see an "elbow", i.e. a point after which the histogram of the proportion of explained variance flattens out, or such that in the cumulative explained variance plot the addition of more components starts to provide "diminishing returns". This would give the number of components retaining more information.

Even though we cannot notice an elbow, there is some evidence of "redundancy", since for example the variance explained by the last two components is negligible.

At this point, we can just see the number of components yielding a cumulative explained variance of at least 95%: usually, this approach ensures that the majority of the data's variability is captured while still achieving a substantial reduction in dimensionality.

The significant proportion of 14 features out of 20 are able to explain 95% of the variance.

Such reduction in dimensionality, even if not drastic, could however still offer benefits such as improved model performance, reduced redundancy, and enhanced interpretability. The key is to evaluate the impact of PCA in our specific case by comparing model performance and understanding the variance captured by the principal components.

There is no division clearly visible in two dimensions.

Although such a division will be evident using non-linear dimensionality reduction technqieues such as UMAP and tSNE, it is still valuable to try PCA as a first step. Indeed, it is computationally less intensive and can provide insights into the variance explained by each component, which can be useful for understanding the overall structure of the data.

tSNE¶

We apply t-distributed Stochastic Neighbour Embedding, which employs a nonlinear approach to embed high-dimensional data into a lower-dimensional space, which in our case we will choose to be two. The core of this method involves minimizing the Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence $$\text{KL}(P\|Q):=\sum_{i\neq j}p_{ij}\log\frac{p_{ij}}{q_{ij}}$$ between the two probability distributions: $P$ in the original high-dimensional space, such that the similarity of datapoint $x_j$ to $x_i$ is the conditional probability $p_{i|j}$, which is assumed to be a Gaussian, constructed so that similar points are assigned higher probabilities, and $Q$ in the lower-dimensional space, similarly constructed.

The goal of the optimization process is to ensure that similar points in the high-dimensional space remain close to each other in the lower-dimensional representation. This helps preserving the local structure of the data, maintaining the relationships and similarities between points even after the dimensionality reduction.

In [37]:
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE
In [38]:

X_tsne = tsne.fit_transform(X)
In [39]:

It is important to note that t-SNE performs a nonlinear transformation on the data, unlike PCA. As a result, the meaning of the axes in the t-SNE plot is not straightforward to interpret.

UMAP¶

We also attempt using UMAP, which stands for Uniform Manifold Approximation and Projection. It is a dimensionality reduction technique operating under the key assumption that the data is uniformly distributed on a Riemannian manifold, which the algorithm endeavors to approximate. By doing so, it effectively captures the intrinsic geometric structure of the data.

We utilize UMAP as an alternative to t-SNE (t-Distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding), leveraging its ability to maintain both the local and global structure of the data.

Hyperparameter optimization¶

Once we have noticed that PCA does actually improve the performance of the classifier, we refine our approach.

We want to find the best combination of hyperparameters that maximize our model's performance, namely: the number of trees ('n_estimators'), the maximum depth of the trees ('max_depth'), the minimum number of samples required to split an internal node ('min_samples_split'), the number of features to consider when looking for the best split ('max_features'), whether to use bootstrap or not ('bootstrap'), and the function to measure the quality of a split ('criterion').

To do this, we first use Cross-Validation to make the choice of the range for the number of trees narrower, and then use Random Search, which samples parameter combinations randomly from specified distributions, with cross-validation, to then train the Random Forest model.

In [63]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
In [64]:
# Define a range of values for n_estimators to try
n_estimators_values = [1, 50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300, 350, 400, 450, 500]

train_scores = []
cv_scores = []
In [65]:
# Iterate over each value of n_estimators
for n_estimators in n_estimators_values:

    rf_classifier = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=n_estimators, random_state=1)
    rf_classifier.fit(X_train_red, y_train)
    
    # Compute training score and append to train_scores
    train_score = rf_classifier.score(X_train_red, y_train)
    train_scores.append(train_score)
    
    # Compute cross-validation score and append to cv_scores
    cv_score = np.mean(cross_val_score(rf_classifier, X_train_red, y_train, cv=5))
    cv_scores.append(cv_score)
In [66]:
# Plot the validation curve
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(n_estimators_values, train_scores, label='Training Score', marker='o', color='royalblue')
plt.plot(n_estimators_values, cv_scores, label='Cross-validation Score', marker='o', color='lightgreen')
plt.xlabel('n_estimators')
plt.ylabel('Score')
plt.title('Validation Curve for Random Forest')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(False)
plt.show()

Since the validation score almost stops increasing, and reaches a "pleateau", after approximately 50 'n_estimators', we reduce the choice of range to analyze, during the hyperparameter optimization, in a small neighbourhood around this value.

In [67]:
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
from scipy.stats import randint

The choice of the sampling distribution for all the hyperparameters is trivial, since all of them are discrete (i.e. we want to search among integer numbers) and in the range chosen all values seem similarly likely: a discrete uniform distribution will work for us.

In [68]:
# Parameter distribution for the Random Search
param_dist = {
    'n_estimators': randint(40, 60), # narrow interval due to CV
    'max_depth': [None, 10, 20, 30], # we select a relatively shallow depth to avoid overfitting
    'min_samples_split': randint(2, 11),
    'min_samples_leaf': randint(1, 5),
    'max_features': [None, 'sqrt', 'log2'], 
    'bootstrap': [True, False],
    'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy']
}

# Get the best parameters from the search
best_params = random_search.best_params_
print("Best parameters found:", best_params)

Best parameters found: {'bootstrap': False, 'criterion': 'gini', 'max_depth': 20, 'max_features': 'log2', 'min_samples_leaf': 1, 'min_samples_split': 5, 'n_estimators': 40}

The criterion selected to assess the quality of a split was the Gini impurity index $$I_G(p):=\sum_i p_i(1-p_i)=1-\sum_i p_i^2$$ which measures how often a randomly chosen element from the set would be incorrectly labeled if it were randomly labeled according to the distribution of labels in the subset, and where indeed $p_i$ is the probability of choosing an item with label $i$.

Accuracy score:  0.89

With the optimal hyperparameters found by Random Search, our Random Forest classifier almost stands still, at an accuracy score of 89%, of which we shall be satisfied. Indeed, we consider this a more "authentic" result than the previous one without optimized parameters, of which the 0.5% higher accuracy could of course be linked to the fortuitous way of splitting of our data between test and train.

Moreover, also the other metrics outline a more satisfying performance, for instance both the precision and the recall, the ratio of correctly predicted positive observations to all observations in the actual class, both stand around 90%, and of course so does their weighted average, the f1-score.

In praticular, class 1 has a slightly higher precision but lower recall compared to Class 0, meaning it makes fewer false positives but misses more actual positives for class 1.

Predictions¶

We have seen that the PCA slightly enhances the performance of our Random Forest Classifier, bringing the accuracy from 87% up to 89%, when passing from the original dataset to the reduced one and when optimized using Random Search. Hence, we are going to use the latter to our test dataset.

Conclusion¶

We first loaded the data, containing 1000 samples for each of the 20 features present, split it into labels and features and explored visually, by means of both separate and "simultaneous" histograms, the distribution of the features, and their "correlation structure". The depth of such structure observed, emboldened us to implement PCA for feature selection: we first tried to notice if an optimal number of principal components could be grasped using the usual "elbow" method, and once this failed, we decided to proceed by selecting 95% explained variance, resulting in 14 components out of 20. However small, this change resulted in a noticeable improvement in the performance of our Random Forest classifier, thus justifying the implementation of Principal Component Analysis, reaching up to an accuracy of 89%, with a Random Search to optimize the hyperparameters of the classifier, based on the results of a previous Cross Validation to narrow down the number of trees.

In perspective, we must admit that our approach was a bit more naive than needed, and one may find some lack of rigorousness, for instance in the choice of the narrow margin of estimators on which we run RandomSearch, done by only relying on the visual intuition yielded by the plot of the CrossValidation score. Also, the number of validations and searches attempted with different "grids" was relatively limited, and the results presented only contain the best performances obtained.

Because of the overall more satisfying performance, we decided to use the Random Forest classifier, with PCA and optimized hyperparameters, to make predictions on the test dataset.
